Explanation:

Three firewalls are added to control incoming and outgoing network traffic.
Firewalls are used to block unauthorized access and only allow approved traffic, such as HTTP, HTTPS, SSH, or database traffic from trusted servers.

An SSL certificate is added so www.foobar.com can be served over HTTPS.
HTTPS encrypts traffic between the user's browser and the website.
This protects sensitive data from being read or modified by attackers.

Monitoring clients are added to collect metrics and logs from the servers.
Monitoring is used to detect failures, performance issues, high traffic, low disk space, memory usage, CPU usage, and service problems.

The monitoring tool collects data through agents installed on each server.
These agents send logs, metrics, and health information to a monitoring service such as Sumologic, Datadog, or New Relic.

To monitor web server QPS, which means queries per second or requests per second, configure the monitoring client to collect Nginx access logs or Nginx status metrics.
The monitoring service can then count how many requests are received each second.

Additional elements:

Firewall 1 protects the load balancer.
Firewall 2 protects Server 1.
Firewall 3 protects Server 2.
The SSL certificate enables encrypted HTTPS traffic.
Monitoring clients allow the team to observe the health and performance of the infrastructure.

Issues:

Terminating SSL at the load balancer level can be an issue because traffic between the load balancer and the backend servers may be unencrypted.
If someone gains access to the internal network, they could read or modify that traffic.

Having only one MySQL server capable of accepting writes is an issue because the Primary database is a single point of failure for writes.
If the Primary database fails, the application may not be able to create, update, or delete data.

Having servers with all the same components can be a problem because web server, application server, and database processes compete for the same CPU, RAM, disk, and network resources.
It also makes scaling harder because each component may need different resources.
For example, the database may need more disk and memory, while the web server may need more network capacity.
